author = {Ben Probyn and Cyrus Daneshvar},
abstract = {Introduction
Point of care ultrasound (POCUS) has a multitude of applications in modern medicine and can be used from both a diagnostic perspective as well as an adjunct to performing invasive medical procedures. POCUS in appropriately trained professionals has revolutionised medical practice.1 However, unregulated adoption of POCUS by inappropriately trained operators can have devastating implications. As such POCUS has been recognised as a top 10 technological hazard for patient safety.2 Furthermore, despite the implementation of the new internal medicine trainee (IMT) curriculum, there is currently no POCUS training requirement for IMTs. This is despite several core procedural skills mandating the use of point of care ultrasound.3,4
Materials and methods
A multicentre survey was designed and distributed via mass email to all internal medicine trainees (IMT1-ST8) across two deaneries in the Southwest of England (Peninsula and Severn). Follow up emails were sent via the assistance of trust wide postgraduate medical education centres or general medicine rota co-ordinators. Non internal medicine trainee responses were subsequently removed.
Results and discussion
41.8% (213/509) doctors training in internal medicine completed the survey. Of these 97.2% (207/213) contributed to either the acute medical take or the general medical rota. 94.8% (202/213) stated that their duties involved performing invasive medical procedures when on call. Despite which only 29.6% (63/213) stated they were ultrasound trained to identify the appropriate sites for undertaking such procedures. 92.0% (196/213) stated they would feel more confident in being able to identify a procedural site following receiving further training on point of care ultrasound. Only 10.8% (23/213) of current trusts provided some form of point of care ultrasound training. 29.6% (63/213) of respondents were aware of any region wide point of care ultrasound training courses and 28.6% (61/213) or respondents had attended such courses. 16.0% (34/213) had formally accredited with a national award body. On a 10-point Likert scale the majority of trainees felt point of care ultrasound training would be useful in their current role (Median = 10, IQR 8-10). A range of free text responses would suggest trainees are very eager to undergo POCUS training with many trainees stating such training should be a core component of IMT. Furthermore, IMTs responses highlight the current dichotomy that exists in the training curriculum. That is, IMTs are expected to be technically proficient at skills that mandate ultrasound training, without any formal ultrasound training requirements in the IMT curriculum. However, concerns have been raised regarding the availability of POCUS facilitators to supply training and assessment, and the frequency of scans to ensure maintenance of skills.
Conclusion
Point of Care ultrasound has a number of applications including being used as an important diagnostic tool and as a key cornerstone to ensuring adequate site selection for invasive medical procedures. Despite the multitude of POCUS applications, few IMT trainees are obtaining sufficient experience or training of POCUS. IMTs perceive POCUS training as highly valuable and would relish in the opportunity for an enhanced POCUS training programme to be delivered (1)Nicholas S, Martin D. Point-of-care ultrasound (POCUS): unnecessary gadgetry or evidence-based medicine? Clinical Medicine. 2018;18(3):219. DOI:10.7861/clinmedicine.18-3-219.(2)Institute E. ECRI Institute. Special report: top 10 health technology hazards for 2020. Plymouth Meeting, ECRI Institute, 2020. 2020(3)Joint Royal Colleges of Physicians Training Board. Curriculum for General internal Medicine (Internal medicine Stage 2) Training Implementation August 2022: https://www.jrcptb.org.uk/sites/default/files/Internal%20Medicine%20%28Stage%202%29%202022%20curriculum%20FINAL%20200522_0.pdf. [Accessed 17 February 2024]4)Joint Royal Colleges of Physicians Training Board. Curriculum for General internal Medicine (Internal medicine Stage 1) Training Implementation August 2019: pdf (jrcptb.org.uk) [Accessed 17 February 2024]}
